Greentown Management Holdings Co. Ltd. (9979. HK) Price Target
From To HK\\$3.51 HK\\$3.20

We hosted a post- results NDR with the CEO. Management reaffirmed that GTM has reached an inflection point, with better cash collection, enhanced quality of new orders, and continued market share gains. Coupled with strong commitment to shareholder returns ( \(\sim 9\%\) yield), we reiterate OW.

- GTM seized dominant position with \(19\%\) y-y new order growth, even though the overall market still faced decline, indicating strong market share gain.- Cash collection recovery on track; management expects more improvement in \(2H_{1}\) , with cash coverage ratio to be back to normal level in the next 2-3 years.- Management emphasized strong commitment to shareholder returns. Together with improving cashflow, we see high visibility of \(\sim 9\%\) dividend yield in 2025-27.

Target of Rmb10bn in new orders in 2025 with better quality: GTM achieved Rmb5bn in new orders in 1H25 (+19% y-y) amid a still weak property market, gaining market share. Growth from POE projects (mostly local non- professional project owners) offset shortfall in low- margin government projects. Overall new order quality was optimized with stabilizing take rate of 2- 3%. Management observed a more rational market this year, marked by fewer price wars and new entrants. As lower- quality players exit, remaining participants are increasingly focused on profitability. With this backdrop, management is confident in securing Rmb10bn in new orders for 2025 (+10% y-y) and sustaining that level in subsequent years (Exhibit 1).

On- track cash collection recovery adds dividend visibility: 1H OCF was Rmb112mn (vs. Rmb77mn in 2024), or 0.4x profit. Given the company's current projects pipeline, management expects a higher cash coverage ratio in 2H and targets a normalized cash coverage ratio (OCF \(\sim 1x\) net profit) in the next 2- 3 years. Together with management's strong commitment to shareholder return, we see high visibility of flat- DPS in 2025 (or Rmb480mn total dividend), implying 9% dividend yield.

Margin pressure largely released, paving the way for earnings turnaround in 2026; price target adjusted to HK\\$3.20: To factor in a slower booking schedule and margin pressure, we forecast a 40% earnings decline in 2025, with growth of 2% for 2026 and 6% for 2027. We apply a 2025E target P/E of 12x (was 9.5x) and a 8% implied yield to reflect the more visible dividend outlook and improving cash flow. Current valuation is attractive at a 9% yield in 2025E- 27E.

We revise our financial forecasts as follows:

Revenue: We lowered our revenue forecasts \(19.4\%\) \(20\%\) and \(23.7\%\) for 2025, 2026, and 2027, respectively, to Rmb2.8bn, Rmb3.0bn, and Rmb3.3bn after factoring in 1H25 results. Gross margin: We lower our gross margin estimates 2.5ppt and 5.1ppt for 2025 and 2026, respectively, to \(45\%\) and \(42.5\%\) to factor in lower take rates from both commercial and government PJM projects amid tightened competition. We estimate \(42.9\%\) gross margin for 2027 with relatively stable segment margins and better revenue mix with less contribution from government projects. Net profit: After reflecting slower revenue booking and lower gross margin, hampered by lower take rate amid rising competition since late 2021, we project net profit to reach Rmb484mn, Rmb495mn, and Rmb523mn, respectively, for 2025, 2026, and 2027, indicating a \(40\%\) decline for 2025 and bottoming earnings with growth rates of \(2\%\) and \(6\%\) for 2026 and 2027, respectively. DPS: Our forecast is unchanged at Rmb0.24/share for 2025- 27, a level similar to 2024, in view of management's strong commitment to shareholder return enhancement, the company's improving cash flow, and sufficient cash balance to support the dividend payment.

We still like GTM in the long term for its dominant market position and continued market share gain amid rising industry competition as well as its asset- light business model with \(\sim 15\%\) ROE and high dividend.
Early mover advantage supports the company's market share gain over the long term.
We expect improving cash collection after policy pivot and local government debt swap program.
Attractive dividend yield of c. \(9\%\) in 2025- 27e is well supported by OCF. Management' is strongly committed to shareholder return.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
